05151nam a2200577Ia 9780520388581DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203885817 a10.1525/97805203885812doi  a(DE-B1597)666775  a(OCoLC)1394118562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a327.721 aLarson, Eric D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrounding Global Justice :bRace, Class, and Grassroots Globalism in the United States and Mexico /cEric D. Larson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I (In)visibilizing Empire: Ambivalent Nationalism and the Origins of Global Justice -- t1. Food Sovereignty: The Origins of an Idea -- t2. Ambivalent Nationalism: Food Sovereignty in Mexico’s Age of NAFTA -- t3. The Specter of US Decline: Ambivalent Americanism and the Jobs with Justice Coalition in the 1980s -- tPart II: Racism and Global Justice in a Multicultural Age -- t4. Against Coca-Colonization: Neoliberal Multiculturalism and Indigenous Insurgency in Southern Mexico -- t5. Obscuring Empire: Color-Blind Anticorporatism and the 1999 World Trade Organization Protests in Seattle -- t6. Invisibilizing Immigration: Color-Blind Anticorporatism and the 1999 World Trade Organization Protests in Seattle -- tPart III: Two Protests grounding global justice in the twenty-first century -- t7. “Localizing” Global Justice: Class, Nation, and the Jobs with Justice Coalition after Seattle -- t8. The WTO Is Back: UNORCA, the Vía Campesina, and the Struggle over Agriculture in Cancún -- t9. The Radical Road to Cancún: Anarchism and Autonomy for the Popular Indigenous Council of Oaxaca—Ricardo Flores Magón -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rise of Trumpism and the Covid-19 pandemic have galvanized debates about globalization. Eric D. Larson presents a timely look at the last time the concept spurred unruly agitation: the late twentieth century. Offering a transnational history of the emergence of the global justice movement in the United States and Mexico, he considers how popular organizations laid the foundations for this “movement of movements.” Farmers, urban workers, and Indigenous peoples grounded their efforts to confront free-market reforms in frontline struggles for economic and racial justice. As they strove to change the direction of the world economy, they often navigated undercurrents of racism, nationalism, and neoliberal multiculturalism, both within and beyond their networks. Larson traces the histories of three popular organizations, examining the Mexican roots of the idea of food sovereignty; racism and whiteness at the momentous Battle of Seattle protests outside the 1999 World Trade Organization meetings; and the rise of dramatic street demonstrations around the globe. Juxtaposing these stories, he reinterprets some of the crucial moments, messages, and movements of the era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook pack